Lab 3: School Districting¶

In this lab, we will investigate school districting.

  • Dataset Overview: Our analysis will make use of 201 census blocks within the jurisdiction of Hope Elementary School District.
  • Assignment Criteria: Each census block will be assigned to a school based on several factors, including the number of elementary students and the fraction of minority race within each block.
  • Optimization Objective: The primary criteria in the assignment process is to minimize travel costs, which can be measured in terms of distance or time, ensuring efficient accessibility for all students within the district. Through this lab, we aim to gain insights into the complex decision-making involved in the creation and optimization of school districts, considering various socio-demographic factors and logistical considerations!

Question 6: Create a new variable, "schools", containing only the schools managed by the Hope Elementary School District. ( 2 pts )¶

Steps:

  1. Download the California school point location shapefile from this data source (https://gis.data.ca.gov/datasets/f7f818b0aa7a415192eaf66f192bc9cc/explore)
  2. Locate the file in Data folder and read the shapefile in this notebook
  3. Take a subset of the file by only including schools within the hope GeoDataFrame ( +1 )
  4. Take another subset, which only includes school that are part of Hope Elementary School district. Assign the subset to a variable, "schools" ( +1 )

NOTE: Every time taking a subset, don't forget to "RESET_INDEX()" !!

Hint
Look into this webpage. (https://www.hopeschooldistrict.org/en-US/schools)
Hope Elementary school district only includes three elementary schools.
Make sure that your schools GeoDataFrame includes only the three elementary schools

Step 2: Optimization Model Preparation¶

This section is to prepare the known information needed for our optimization model, and set parameters.

In [22]:
# Tolerance is about how much you'd like to allow each school to deviate from the ideal capacity, which is the total number of students / the number of schools
TOLERANCE = 1.2 # 1.2 will allow schools to deviate by 20 %

Task: Set the I, J value correctly.¶

Things to consider.

  • I is the total number of blocks
  • J is the total number of schools
In [23]:
I = 201
J = 3

Task: Prepare $S_i$ and $N_i$ variables for the model.¶

$S_i$ must be an array of the elementary student population at each block
$N_i$ must be an array of the elementary student population in minority race at each block

In [24]:
S_i = blocks['elpop']
White_array = blocks['elwpop']
N_i = S_i - White_array

Task: Prepare $C_j$ variable for the model.¶

$C_j$ indicates that it's an array. In that case, different capacity constraint is assigned to each school.
However, for our convenience, let's do integer capacity this time.
As we will set $C_j$ variable as an integer, let's use a notation, $C$.
The $C$ integer value will be calculated by following steps.

  1. The total elementary student population across the blocks
  2. Divided by the number of schools (which is equal to J)
  3. Multiplied by TOLERANCE
In [25]:
C = (832/J)*1.2

Question 7: Prepare $D_{ij}$ variable for the model. ( 2 pts )¶

$D_{ij}$ represents a two-dimensional array with two subscripts, $i$ and $j$.

Considerations:

  • The first subscript $i$ denotes the row index in the two-dimensional array, corresponding to a block with index $i$.
  • The second subscript $j$ denotes the column index in the two-dimensional array, representing a school with index $j$.
    • For instance, if we have 100 blocks and 10 schools, $D_{ij}$ would be a two-dimensional array (or matrix) of shape (100, 10), consisting of 100 rows and 10 columns.
    • Consequently, $D_{ji}$ would be a matrix of shape (10, 100), containing 10 rows and 100 columns.

  • $D_{ij}$ denotes that given a row index $i$ and column index $j$, a specific value can be retrieved, which represents the distance between the $i$th block and the $j$th school.

    • For example, $D_{12}$ would indicate the distance between the second block and the third school.

Given that, let's create the $D_ij$ variable.

In [26]:
distances = blocks.geometry.apply(lambda geom: schools.distance(geom))
D_ij = distances.to_numpy()
In [27]:
# Check the shape of your two-dimensional array, D_ij.

Question 8: Choose upper and lower thresholds for the minority race fraction at each school and provide reasoning for your selection. ( 2 pts )¶

In [28]:
FN_high = (.56)
FN_low = (.16)

Write your answer in this markdown cell!

This values come from the total district containing a 36% population of non white or asian population which I am considering minorities as asian communities tend to mix and interact with white communities while facing relatively minor discrimination when compared to the other minorities. Then to create the minimum and maximum thresholds I simply added and subtracted 20% from that precentage getting 16% and 56%. This will allow the model to create a school with a majority minority communities, while still requiring all of the schools to possess some amount of minority communities spreading the tax money around between the white and minority communities more evenley. This has the added benefit of allowing for a white population to never exceed 85% of a school, but allowing for the model to create a school that is not white majority despite being a general majority in the community.

Step 3: Optimization ( Wei et al., 2021 )¶

The model presented in the paper:

\begin{align*} \text{minimize} \quad & \sum_{i=1}^{I} \sum_{j=1}^{J} D_{ij} \cdot S_i \cdot x_{ij} \\ \text{subject to} \quad & \sum_{j=1}^{J} x_{ij} = 1 \quad \text{for } i = 1, \ldots, I \\ & \sum_{i=1}^{I} x_{ij} \cdot S_i \leq C_j \quad \text{for } j = 1, \ldots, J \\ & \sum_{i=1}^{I} (FN_{\text{low}} \cdot S_i - N_i) \cdot x_{ij} \leq 0 \quad \text{for } j = 1, \ldots, J \\ & \sum_{i=1}^{I} (N_i - FN_{\text{high}} \cdot S_i) \cdot x_{ij} \leq 0 \quad \text{for } j = 1, \ldots, J \\ & x_{ij} \in \{0,1\} \quad \text{for } i = 1, \ldots, I \text{ and } j = 1, \ldots, J \end{align*}

Question 9: Construct the School Districting Optimization Model using the provided skeleton code structure. ( 5 pts )¶

In [29]:
model = gp.Model("School Districts")

# Create decision variables
x = model.addVars(I, J, vtype=GRB.BINARY, name = "x")

# Set objective
model.setObjective(gp.quicksum(D_ij[i,j]*S_i[i]*x[i,j] for i in range(I) for j in range(J)), GRB.MINIMIZE)

# Add constraints
# Constraint 1
model.addConstrs(gp.quicksum(x[i,j] for j in range(J)) == 1 for i in range(I))
                   
# Constraint 2
model.addConstrs(gp.quicksum(x[i,j] * S_i[i] for i in range(I)) <= C for j in range(J))

# Constraint 3
model.addConstrs(gp.quicksum(x[i,j]*(FN_low*S_i[i]-N_i[i]) for i in range(I)) <=0 for j in range(J))


# Constraint 4
model.addConstrs(gp.quicksum(x[i,j]*(N_i[i]-FN_high *S_i[i]) for i in range(I)) <= 0 for j in range (J))


# Optimize model
model.optimize()

def evaluate_assignment(col = "curr_assigned"):
    popsums = []
    FNs = []
    Travel_ds = []
    for j in range(J):
        school_blocks = blocks.loc[blocks[col]==j]
        popsum = school_blocks.elpop.sum()
        wsum = school_blocks.elwpop.sum()
        FNs.append((1 - wsum/popsum)*100)
        popsums.append(popsum)
        
        Travel_d = 0
        for i in school_blocks.index:
            Travel_d += D_ij[i][j] * S_i[i]
        Travel_ds.append(Travel_d / popsum)
    print(f"Mean Travel Distance (m) is {np.mean(Travel_ds)}") 
    return pd.DataFrame({'School':schools.SchoolName, 'Capacity':popsums, 'FN':FNs, "Travel_ds (m)": Travel_ds})

Question 10: Share insights gleaned from the analysis of the school districting process. Feel free to discuss with Step 6 result. ( 2 pts )¶

You can discuss about..

  • Minority Fraction bounds
  • Capacity constraints
  • Distance metric
  • and so on!

Write your answer in this markdown cell!

The current system is functional, it has a somewhat equatable fraction of minority students concentrated in each school, allowing for them to both have a say in the school while not making any of them travel too far. However it is not optimised the model we ran created a much better answer for this problem, with a optimised travel distance while maintaining the minimised travel distance. That said the random model has a great distribution of the minority community with the white population. 
I find the idea of trying to set a minority bound by a single researcher a dangerous one. It is the sort of thing that a lay person who was not intimately familiar with the model would not notice but depending on what the goal of  the redistricting is it makes a huge difference. If the goal is to minimise the distance to school having narrow range that distributes them to the most optimal school option will allow all of the students to have the most optimal distance to school. However if the goal is to concentrate them somewhat allowing for them to have representation in the governmental systems that run their lives and not just being so dispersed that they don't have a voice, setting more restrictive bounds with a high upper limit and a low lower limit to allow for some of the schools to have very few minority groups while some have a majority of minority groups. 
Distance metrics can be difficult as a euclidean (straight line distance) makes for rather circular districts where students are able to travel as the crow flies between their block and the school. However by allowing for a bit of network analysis the students then have a farther drive as few roads are in a perfectly straight line from school to home. This leads to a distribution that tends to align with roads and other physical features. Interesting was the degree to which the distance metrics make a difference, by simply changing constraints to follow roads the mean distance travelled almost doubled for the optimised option. It made the mean almost as long as it was without optimisation. 
The most surprising takeaway from this lab was the (relative) ease which this analysis was done, by allowing math majors to make gurobi solver allows for non mathematicians to apply this incredible tool to real problems. However that is not always a good thing, it means that I lack a lot of the understanding of what is going on behind the scene of the packages that I import and run. Thus there are some serious black box concerns both for bad actors changing results, but also for simple misuse of this tool as the user may not necessarily understand what it is doing so the tool is then run in a suboptimal/ or problematic way.

Step 6. Network Distance Utilization¶

In this section, network distance will be utilized in the optimization procedure instead of Euclidean distance.
You will be asked to copy and paste the code from the previous steps to the designated location.
The Origin-Destination matrix can be found in the file "driving_od_matrix.csv", and the geometry for each path is provided in "routes.shp".

In [54]:
# Read the driving origin-destination (OD) matrix from a CSV file
od = pd.read_csv("Data/driving_od_matrix.csv")

# Initialize a matrix D_ij to store driving distances between each block and each school
D_ij = np.ones((len(blocks), len(schools))) * -1

# Populate the D_ij matrix with driving distances from the OD matrix
for o in range(len(od)):
    # Extract the origin and destination IDs from the OD matrix
    i, j = od.loc[o, ["OriginID", "DestinationID"]]
    # Store the driving distance in meters in the corresponding cell of D_ij matrix
    D_ij[i - 1][j - 1] = od.loc[o, "Total_Kilometers"] * 1000

# Check if all elements of the D_ij matrix are non-negative, indicating valid driving distances
(D_ij >= 0).sum() == len(blocks) * len(schools)

# Copy and Paste your optimization model above!

model = gp.Model("School Districts")

# Create decision variables
x = model.addVars(I, J, vtype=GRB.BINARY, name = "x")

# Set objective
model.setObjective(gp.quicksum(D_ij[i,j]*S_i[i]*x[i,j] for i in range(I) for j in range(J)), GRB.MINIMIZE)

# Add constraints
# Constraint 1
model.addConstrs(gp.quicksum(x[i,j] for j in range(J)) == 1 for i in range(I))
                   
# Constraint 2
model.addConstrs(gp.quicksum(x[i,j] * S_i[i] for i in range(I)) <= C for j in range(J))

# Constraint 3
model.addConstrs(gp.quicksum(x[i,j]*(FN_low*S_i[i]-N_i[i]) for i in range(I)) <=0 for j in range(J))


# Constraint 4
model.addConstrs(gp.quicksum(x[i,j]*(N_i[i]-FN_high *S_i[i]) for i in range(I)) <= 0 for j in range (J))


# Optimize model
model.optimize()
